6. Six years later he died of stroke on March 24, 1922, leaving her widowed at 30. She returned to Germany in 1925 to begin her artistic apprenticeship."},{"number":3,"category":"legacy","header":"Her work in Harvard, Philadelphia, and Chile museums","body":"Her work is held by the Philadelphia Museum of Art, the Museo de la Solidaridad Salvador Allende in Santiago, Chile, and the Harvard Art Museums. She is buried beside her husband at Mount Feake Cemetery, Waltham — the Adams family ground."}],"cross_connections":[],"sources":[{"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marta_Adams","label":"Wikipedia — Marta Adams"}],"former_ids":[],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002"}],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"is_placeholder":false,"residence":{},"baptism":{},"slug":"marta-arnstem-1891"},"I00303":{"id":"I00303","bio":{"display_name":"Doctor Benjamin Faneuil Dunkin Adams","first_name":"Benjamin","middle_name":"Faneuil Dunkin","last_name":"Adams","married_names":[],"title":"Doctor","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777485306/benjaminadams_vrm9zs.jpg"},"birth":{"year":1839,"month":4,"day":13,"city":"Waltham","state":"Massachusetts"},"death":{"year":1895,"month":10,"day":28,"city":"Colorado Springs","state":"Colorado","cause":"tuberculosis (long-term)"},"gender":"male","parents":{"father_name":"Dr. Horatio Adams","mother_name":"Ann Bethune Dunkin"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD3341","children_ids":["HD3347","HD3348","HD3349"],"date_year":1868,"end_year":1895,"end_type":"death"}],"number_of_marriages":1,"has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":["physician","harvard_graduate"],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["medicine","social_reform"],"notable_blurb":"Waltham physician; Colorado College trustee; civic leader","primary_url":"https://www.thecrimson.com/article/1895/11/2/obituary-dr-benjamin-faneuil-dunkin-adams/","primary_url_label":"Harvard Crimson obituary"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Harvard 1860, Harvard Medical highest honors 1864","body":"He graduated from Harvard in 1860 and immediately began studying medicine with Dr. Jeffries Wyman of Cambridge, soon entering Harvard Medical School. He took his MD in 1864 with the highest honors after surgical interneships at Rainsford Island state hospital and Massachusetts General Hospital, then studied in London and Paris."},{"number":2,"category":"death","header":"Tuberculosis forced retirement to Colorado at 43","body":"Overwork in Waltham broke his health in 1882 and he moved his family to Colorado Springs. Though he never resumed practice, he led an active civic life there until his death in 1895 — Colorado College trustee from 1887, friend and patron of the Colorado Springs Gazette editor Steele."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Descended from Peter Faneuil and Israel Putnam","body":"He counted among his ancestors Peter Faneuil — who gave his name to Faneuil Hall — and Israel Putnam, the famous Revolutionary War general. His mother Ann Bethune Dunkin carried the South Carolina Dunkin line; the unusual middle name 'Faneuil Dunkin' was inherited."}],"cross_connections":[],"sources":[{"url":"https://www.thecrimson.com/article/1895/11/2/obituary-dr-benjamin-faneuil-dunkin-adams/","label":"Harvard Crimson obituary Nov 2, 1895"},{"label":"Colorado Springs Gazette tribute Oct 30, 1895"}],"former_ids":[],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002"}],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"is_placeholder":false,"reside